<a href="javascript:card_browser(39)">Troop of Uruk-hai</a> x 2<br>
Lurz, SOI <br>
Savagerty to Match Their Numbers x 3<br>
Sarumans Ambition x 2<br>
Sarumans Power <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(944)">Beyond the Height of Men</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(57)">Worry</a><br>
Can You Protect Me From Yourself x 2<br>
Abandoning Reason for Madness x 3<br>
(6 Nazguls, 4 Sarumans &  13 Uruk-hais with 3 Captains to pull them again = 23 minion + 3 Madness out of a 37 card shadow side)<br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Edit<br>
The One Ring, Islidur&#39;s Heir is of course The One Ring, Islidur&#39;s BANE! :)<br>
And its 3 instead of 4 Sarumans, 22 minions <br>
<br>
Introduction<br>
This is an improved version of the Nazgul / Uruk-hai Split Deck I played on Day 1 of the Australian Continentals. The fellowship is a serious one but the shadow side is slightly more experimental and conceptual. The original (and weaker than this deck) went 4-3 losing to the eventual Day 1 winner and runner ups but hadnt managed to win against any other top Australian players. The improvements should make it a better deck. And please rate it as a FUN deck - the category on which it is submitted. And yes, I was mad enough to play with a fun deck at a top tier tournament. That said I do believe that it could do well in local tournaments.<br>
<br>
Meta:<br>
The deck was designed with the intention to defeat overwhelming numbers of Uruk-hai decks; with the top player to beat playing a strong Moria deck, hence the inclusion of cards like Frying Pan, Aragorns Bow x 2 & PATHS x 3. Sauron is non-existent in Australia.<br>
<br>
Starting:<br>
I have redesigned this deck so it can flexibly bid anywhere from 0-8! I myself prefer to bid 0 if I dont have any idea of what the person is playing, 8 if its an important match up and I know that the person is not playing Nazgul and Sauron. But generally anywhere from 4-7 depending whether you are familiar with your local meta.<br>
<br>
I know this is against generally accepted thinking but bidding 0 is not a bad idea because you are playing half Nazgul. Sometimes when my opponent sees Weathertop and Nazgul, they might be more cautious to double to the Ford and stop. I was bidding 0 in 13 of my 15 games (and 6 in 2 of my important games, but I had Defender + 1 Sam in my deck then) and the deck and its Pure Uruk-hai version (Madness 1.0) performed fine.<br>
<br>
This gives you a chance to start strongly with one additional reconciliation phase and also give you the chance to double to 3. Also against generally accepted thinking, not having Ford is not a big deal in this deck. The important purpose of the mixed package is to give you an opportunity to kill your opponents companions throughout the entire game and helping you stay ahead. <br>
<br>
Flexible starting situations:<br>
1. Bid 0 <br>
If non-The Prancing Pony Start:<br>
Play Aragorn.<br>
If The Prancing Pony Start:<br>
Play Arwen & Legolas and pull Aragorn<br>
<br>
2. Bid high 4-8<br>
Loses bid, If non-The Prancing Pony Start<br>
Play Aragorn<br>
Wins bid or Loses bid, If The Prancing Pony Start<br>
Play Sam & Legolas, get rid of burdens where applicable and pull Aragorn<br>
<br>
The interesting flexibility about these starts is that you can safely bid up to 8 if you are sure that you arent playing against pure Nazguls or Saurons (Enduring Evil is going to be ugly). Traitors Voice and other weird cards are not typically seen. You might ask what about the lone Uruk Berserker or lone Enquea in the deck. How you play the beginning phase is critical:<br>
<br>
If bid 8 and win (typical):<br>
You start Sam & Legolas, get rid of burdens, pulls Aragorn giving the opponent 4 twilight and 6 burdens, you move forward to Ettenmoors (typical site for non-Nazgul). You now have 6 burdens and 4+4+2-2 = 8 twilight.<br>
Enquea (8 twilight): exerts to kill Legolas, Aragorn exerts twice to become power 12 and kills Enquea (if at Ettenmoors) or if you managed to have any of these 5 cards, Aragorns Bow or PATHS, kill Enquea with it. If he exerts to exhause Aragorn, Legolas  natural archery = dead Enquea. Otherwise stop. Next site you are giving them 3 twilight which means 0 minions. <br>
Berserker: exerts to exhaust Legolas or Aragorn  natural archery = dead berserker. Next site you are giving them 4 (3+1 leftover) twilight which generally means 0 minions too. If he think hes smart and doesnt exert to exhaust, sacrifice Frodo to bring burdens down to zero, natural archery for one wound, Aragorn to take 2 damage, next turn, exert Legolas twice get rid of the Berserker.<br>
<br>
A couple of points of these starts are:<br>
1. Playing LOTR at high levels is about risk management, do you dare to bid 8? The chances of getting a first turn Berserker or Enquea is typically quite slim and not as bad as people think.<br>
2. Dont over deploy at the beginning. One or two extra twilight at the beginning especially if you are bidding 8 is extremely dangerous, just dont do it.<br>
<br>
Some discussion about card choices:<br>
1. Weathertop?<br>
Instead of Bree Streets, Weatherhills or Ettenmoors; it thought that Weathertop fitted well in my deck. It doesnt give your opponent that much advantage as compared to Bree Streets and Weatherhills if hes playing Nazguls as well. It also gives that extra 1 twilight expecially if hes playing extreme choke (Aragorn and Frodo only) to get down Twilight Nelya or a 3 twilight Uruk Warrior to convince him to stop. I think it is a toss up between Ettenmoor or Weathertop depending on your preference.<br>
<br>
2. Hollin instead of Eregion Hills?<br>
Hollin still helps more with convincing your opponent to stop at site 3 with a live Troop of Uruk-hai and prevents hand clog better.<br>
<br>
3. Can You Protect Me From Yourself?<br>
The heart of this deck. Usually people are so reliant of Aragorn and will do everything but to exhaust him. If the first character you deploy at Weathertop is a 3 cost Uruk-hai, they will typically take the burdens, especially if they only have Aragorn as the main fighting character then. If they double move to the unexpected Ford down comes Toldea or Nelya or Enquea and the opponent will be in a world of pain. The surprise has even caused people to sacrifice Sam instead which will then take out the typical source of burden reduction and cause even more pain later.<br>
<br>
4. Armor x 3?<br>
Uruk-hai is the most popular deck played by experienced players in Australia right now, 3 Armors help lots.<br>
<br>
5. PATHS x 3 and Frying Pan?<br>
I wanted to defeat the eventual Australian champ who was playing Moria at the time. Good against other shadow cards too (PATHS anyway)<br>
<br>
6. Secret Sentinels x 3?<br>
I wanted to defeat the eventual Australian champ who was playing Moria at the time, and easy card to get rid of; just cancel conditions during your second move against Nazguls and Uruk-Hai.<br>
<br>
7. Abandoning Reason for Madness x 3?<br>
This is one of my favorite cards. It suits this deck especially because it is typically more efficient to play Uruk-hai in the later sites than Nazguls (unless they happen to be stuck with 5 burdens or more). These cards let you get rid of the heavier costs Nazgul, helps against choke to get rid of other more expensive minions like Saruman, Lurtzs and Berserkers, and finally helps prepare cards one or two turn in advance for both your fellowship AND shadow side. It has won me a couple of important games during the Australian championship. If you dont like it, just get rid of the 3 and on the fellowship 1 Cart, 1 Shards and another card to make the deck a respectable 68 instead of 74. And remember, its FREE with 1 Sarumans Ambition in play.<br>
<br>
8. Selection of Nazguls?<br>
The most prominent question I guest is why 1 Enquea only. Mostly because I thought Toldea and Attea will actually win more battles than Enquea with that extra +1 power. Twilight Nelya (site 2 minion) because it is very easy to have more than 1 burden at the beginning stage and fierce and damage+1 (damage +2 with 3 burdens and Nazgul sword) just stops an unlucky fellowship like nothing else :)<br>
<br>
9. Worry?<br>
Helps increase the burdens just in case.<br>
<br>
10. Traitors Voice?<br>
I didnt like the requirements of exertion and 2 twilight. Besides if they are stuck at 5+ burdens, there will be other better ways to discourage them from double moving  Toldeas, Enqueas and Berserker  Captain combo.<br>
<br>
11. Uruk Captains x 3<br>
Typically more than the usual two but the Combo of Captain with Lurtz or Berserker (if 5 burdens) or just Troop of Uruk-hai helps discourage double moving.<br>
<br>
12. Uruk Ravager?<br>
I didnt like the Ravager because it will only cost 2 if you have Saruman AND 8 twilights at the start (other than in the slopes). Since it is situational, Id rather play with the definitely 3 cost Lieutenant or Warrior. Once again this depends on your preference.<br>
<br>
13. Gandalfs Cart and Shards of Narsil?<br>
These cards help unclog my hand since Im playing with doubles of Aragorns weapons, 3 Armors and the Frying Pan. Shards because I typically keep my companions at 4 against Uruk-hai and I can stack extra or overtly early copies of Boromir, LOG. Note that you can stack the Shards on the Cart :). As mentioned above, get rid of these two and another fellowship along with the 3 Madness if thats not your style to make it to a reasonable 68 card deck. Note that you can deploy the frying pan on Filbert to clear your hand.<br>
<br>
14. Elrond, Herald to Gilgalad?<br>
I found this card to be much better than the FOTR version. Drawing the extra 3 cards is not too important for me here because the throughput of this deck is quite excellent, in all of my 15 Continental games I didnt really have a bad draw (which I attribute to the ease by which I can clear my hand). This ROTEL version however usually helps me heal Boromir with Armor to take on that extra big minion or helps heal Aragorn or Legolas for that one critical point of directed archery. It is also very resilient against Tower Assassin because his exertion only occurs in the regroup phase when you generally know whether the Assassin is a threat (unless double moving).<br>
<br>
15. No Pathfinder or Thrors Map?<br>
The original deck had both but I wanted to keep the deck from going too large. In addition, the main purpose of the site 6 elves are to help your double move from 4-6. With Aragorn, HTTWC and Galadriel, elves also come down free or very cheaply. Losing them was never critical to any of my games. With Pathfinder, I often got it too early to be of any use; with Thrors Map, Id rather saved the extra exertion on Hobbits. If you feel uncomfortable with it, I suggest playing one more Hobbit (bounder or Merry or Pippin) and the Thrors Map; and you can always play the Pathfinder as a regroup action regardless of whether you want to or can move again.<br>
<br>
Final comments:<br>
Id played this deck as my day 1 deck because if word gets around that Im playing split Nazgul and the Ford on day 1, people will be less reluctant to bid high against me on day 2 or to be less likely to double to the Ford. I have to be honest, that didnt work and people played as per normal against me. People did stop at site 2 against me on day 1 thought after seeing a first turn Nazgul or weathertop alone.<br>
<br>
I think I have written enough about this deck. To see it in action, I refer you to my tournament report (10000+ words long!) Scrub to Grub and Scrub to Grub Part II. Except for some improvements, the shadow side was played in day 1 while the fellowship side was played for both day 1 and 2.<br>
